</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1EA273C55717FFA955E8FEDFFE26DF37" pageId="2" pageNumber="334" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5607204E5717FFA955E8FEDFFDF7DE43" blockId="2.[151,1437,150,789]" pageId="2" pageNumber="334">
<emphasis id="64CCFC5C5717FFA955E8FEDFFEBBDD63" bold="true" box="[199,315,295,321]" pageId="2" pageNumber="334">Remarks.</emphasis>
The species derives its name from the cyan colour of the gut, very likely due to the cyanobacteria on which it feeds on. The bluish colouration was reported in the original description of the species by 
<bibRefCitation id="32295DBF5717FFA95012FEB3FF64DDAB" author="Brunson, R. B." pageId="2" pageNumber="334" pagination="325 - 352" refId="ref11582" refString="Brunson, R. B. (1950) An introduction to the taxonomy of the Gastrotricha with a study of eighteen species from Michigan. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 69, 325 - 352. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3223127" type="journal article" year="1950">Brunson (1950)</bibRefCitation>
, and has been recently observed in specimens from the 
<collectingCountry id="2EAF60DE5717FFA95670FE97FC03DDAB" box="[863,899,367,393]" name="United States of America" pageId="2" pageNumber="334">US</collectingCountry>
collected by Dr. Bas Kooijmanone (see picture at http://www.gastrotricha.unimore.it/picturegallery.htm). One of us (MAT) has seen gastrotrichs with a bluish gut content during his expedition in 
<collectingCountry id="2EAF60DE5717FFA95726FE4FFD19DDF3" box="[521,665,439,465]" name="South Africa" pageId="2" pageNumber="334">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="32295DBF5717FFA957CEFE4FFC37DDF3" author="Todaro, M. A. &amp; Perissinotto, R. &amp; Bownes, S. J." box="[737,951,439,465]" pageId="2" pageNumber="334" pagination="77 - 94" refId="ref14103" refString="Todaro, M. A., Perissinotto, R. &amp; Bownes, S. J. (2013) Neogosseidae (Gastrotricha, Chaetonotida) from the iSimangaliso Wetland Park, KwaZulu-Natal, South Africa. Zookeys, 315, 77 - 94. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 315.5593" type="journal article" year="2013">
Todaro 
<emphasis id="64CCFC5C5717FFA95617FE4FFCEBDDF3" box="[824,875,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="334">et al</emphasis>
. 2013
</bibRefCitation>
); size and general appearance of the South African specimens are very similar to the American species (MAT, unpublished). Gastrotrich specimens identified as 
<taxonomicName id="91B85BCD5717FFA95599FE07FEF7DE3A" authorityName="Brunson" authorityYear="1950" box="[182,375,511,537]" family="Chaetonotidae" genus="Chaetonotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chaetonotida" pageId="2" pageNumber="334" phylum="Gastrotricha" rank="species" species="gastrocyaneus">
<emphasis id="64CCFC5C5717FFA95599FE07FEF7DE3A" box="[182,375,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="334">C. gastrocyaneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been found twice in 
<collectingCountry id="2EAF60DE5717FFA957B1FE07FD5ADE3B" box="[670,730,511,537]" name="India" pageId="2" pageNumber="334">India</collectingCountry>
, respectively by 
<bibRefCitation id="32295DBF5717FFA956B8FE07FBBEDE3B" author="Sharma, B. K." box="[919,1086,511,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="334" pagination="319 - 322" refId="ref13805" refString="Sharma, B. K. (1987) Gastrotricha (Freshwater). In: Fauna of Orissa. State Fauna Series 1, Zoological Survey of India, Calcutta, pp. 319 - 322." type="book chapter" year="1987">Sharma (1987)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="32295DBF5717FFA9515AFE07FA18DE3B" author="Sharma, S. &amp; Sharma, B. K." box="[1141,1432,511,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="334" pagination="1 - 307" refId="ref13880" refString="Sharma, S. &amp; Sharma, B. K. (2008) Zooplankton Diversity in Floodplain Lakes of Assam. Records of the Zoological Survey of India Occasional Paper, No. 290, 1 - 307." type="book chapter" year="2008">Sharma &amp; Sharma (2008)</bibRefCitation>
. Surprisingly neither 
<bibRefCitation id="32295DBF5717FFA954AEFDDBFD27DE1F" author="Sharma B. K. &amp; Sharma S." box="[385,679,547,573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="334" pagination="211 - 215" refId="ref13843" refString="Sharma B. K. &amp; Sharma S. (1990) On some Freshwater Gastrotricha from N. E. Region. Records of the Zoological Survey of India, 86, 211 - 215." type="journal article" year="1990">Sharma &amp; Sharma (1990)</bibRefCitation>
nor 
<bibRefCitation id="32295DBF5717FFA957F1FDDBFC60DE1F" author="Purushothaman, J." box="[734,992,547,573]" pageId="2" pageNumber="334" pagination="8115 - 125" refId="ref12913" refString="Purushothaman, J. (2017) Gastrotricha. Chapter 8. In: Chandra, K., Gopi, K. C., Rao, D. V., Valarmathi, K. &amp; Alfred, J. R. B. (Eds.), Current Status of Freshwater Faunal Diversity in India. Published by the Director, Zoological. Survey of India, Kolkata, pp. 8115 - 125." type="book chapter" year="2017">Purushothaman (2017)</bibRefCitation>
did mention this species name in their lists of freshwater Gastrotricha from 
<collectingCountry id="2EAF60DE5717FFA95719FDBFFDF3DE43" box="[566,627,583,609]" name="India" pageId="2" pageNumber="334">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5607204E5717FFA955E8FD93FE26DF37" blockId="2.[151,1437,150,789]" pageId="2" pageNumber="334">
Morphometric data provided for the Indian specimens are very scanty and the authors never mentioned these gastrotrichs to have a cyan-coloured intestine, which is a trademark trait for the species. Because of the poor morphological data and in the absence of any reference to the colour of their gut, we consider the identification performed so far of these Indian specimens to be unreliable; consequently, 
<taxonomicName id="91B85BCD5717FFA95693FD2FFBFEDED2" authorityName="Brunson" authorityYear="1950" box="[956,1150,727,753]" family="Chaetonotidae" genus="Chaetonotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chaetonotida" pageId="2" pageNumber="334" phylum="Gastrotricha" rank="species" species="gastrocyaneus">
<emphasis id="64CCFC5C5717FFA95693FD2FFBFEDED2" box="[956,1150,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="334">C. gastrocyaneus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should not be considered part of the Indian fauna.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
